# Login mechanics вАФ PAM & startup files

## PAM вАФ how you're authenticated

Login, `su`, `sudo` don't check credentials themselves вАФ they call **PAM**. So auth is *config*, not code (2FA, LDAP, complexity = drop in a module). Config: **`/etc/pam.d/`**, one file per service.

| Group | Handles |
|---|---|
| **`auth`** | prove who you are |
| **`account`** | allowed right now? (expired/locked) |
| **`password`** | change rules вАФ complexity, history |
| **`session`** | setup/teardown вАФ mount home, log, limits |

вЪ†пЄП A PAM mistake locks you out вАФ keep a root session open while editing.

## Shell startup files вАФ what runs on entry

- **Login shell** (TTY, SSH, `su -`) вЖТ `/etc/profile` вЖТ `~/.bash_profile`
- **Interactive non-login** (new terminal) вЖТ `/etc/bash.bashrc` вЖТ **`~/.bashrc`**

Convention: **`~/.bashrc`** = aliases, functions, prompt ¬Ј **`~/.bash_profile`** = `export`s, `PATH` (usually just sources `~/.bashrc`). The module 03 dotfiles вАФ `source ~/.bashrc` to apply.
